WEBVTT

00:00.195 --> 00:01.664
Beth, you have a minute?

00:01.672 --> 00:03.351
<i>Previously on</i> This Is Us...

00:03.483 --> 00:04.483
We have to let you go.

00:04.883 --> 00:06.116
BETH: <i>This is Beth Pearson.</i>

00:06.141 --> 00:09.110
I was checking to see
if you got the résumé.

00:09.287 --> 00:11.092
But I hadn't heard anything, so...

00:11.117 --> 00:13.726
if you could, uh, call me back?

00:14.305 --> 00:16.679
Your last boss, Bill,
couldn't rave about you more.

00:17.547 --> 00:19.242
That must have been hard parting ways.

00:19.406 --> 00:22.952
Yeah. (CLEARS THROAT)
Sorry, it's still a little raw.

00:23.053 --> 00:24.234
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY, SNIFFLES)

00:24.259 --> 00:26.773
- My mom hurt her damn hip again.
- She okay?

00:26.798 --> 00:29.399
Yeah. I just hope
she didn't break it again.

00:29.512 --> 00:31.265
Um, I got to head down to D.C.

00:31.290 --> 00:33.265
- Of course. When?
- Now.

00:35.214 --> 00:37.059
("I SAY A LITTLE PRAYER"
BY ARETHA FRANKLIN PLAYING)

00:37.083 --> 00:40.085
♪ Say a little prayer for you ♪

00:41.719 --> 00:43.843
♪ The moment I wake up ♪

00:45.076 --> 00:48.645
- ♪ Before I put on my makeup
- ♪ <i>Makeup</i> ♪

00:48.670 --> 00:51.472
- ♪ I say a little
- ♪ <i>Prayer for you</i> ♪

00:51.829 --> 00:53.306
(SCHOOL BELL RINGS, STUDENTS MURMURING)

00:53.330 --> 00:57.667
♪ And while combing my hair now
and wondering what dress... ♪

00:57.802 --> 01:00.343
Damon. Damon Henderson.

01:01.085 --> 01:03.617
Mr. Henderson, I know you hear me.

01:04.726 --> 01:07.234
Mrs. Sawicky said
you were late for homeroom.

01:07.259 --> 01:10.045
- Again.
- I'm sorry, Principal Clarke.

01:10.070 --> 01:11.859
Oh, you don't have to apologize to me.

01:11.945 --> 01:14.984
Apologize to yourself,
and don't let it happen again.

01:16.181 --> 01:17.390
Yes, ma'am.

01:19.655 --> 01:20.960
- Oh.
- (SNAPS FINGERS)

01:21.243 --> 01:23.273
I got a "B" on my history exam today.

01:23.808 --> 01:24.968
Okay.

01:25.312 --> 01:26.546
Last time, I got a "C."

01:26.571 --> 01:29.062
So next time you get an "A." Go on, now.

01:29.359 --> 01:31.294
Don't be late for third period, too.

01:31.395 --> 01:34.096
♪ Please love me true ♪

01:34.742 --> 01:35.812
♪ This is my prayer... ♪

01:35.867 --> 01:37.342
No running! There is no run...

01:37.367 --> 01:40.169
- Ow!
- Ooh! My bad, Principal Clarke.

01:40.695 --> 01:41.959
Oh, God.

01:41.984 --> 01:43.584
BOY: Are you okay, Mrs. Clarke?

01:43.685 --> 01:45.019
I'm fine, Donald. Keep going.

01:45.044 --> 01:46.311
Go on, go on.

01:46.382 --> 01:47.781
(GROANING, WINCING)

01:49.027 --> 01:54.218
synced and corrected by susinz
*www.addic7ed.com*

01:59.171 --> 02:00.401
You okay?

02:00.536 --> 02:01.601
Yeah, I'm fine.

02:01.820 --> 02:02.881
(TLC'S "WHAT ABOUT
YOUR FRIENDS" PLAYING)

02:02.905 --> 02:06.140
- Yes! '90s on 9 for life! Ha!
- (TURNS UP VOLUME)

02:06.275 --> 02:09.014
Remember when we used to pretend
we were in this music video?

02:09.038 --> 02:11.312
♪ What about your friends? ♪

02:11.337 --> 02:13.371
♪ Are they gonna be lowdown? ♪

02:13.474 --> 02:17.094
♪ Will they ever be around? Hey ♪

02:17.312 --> 02:19.448
♪ Or will they turn
their backs on you? ♪

02:19.473 --> 02:20.606
♪ Every now and then ♪

02:20.631 --> 02:22.351
- (BOTH LAUGH)
- ♪ I get a little crazy... ♪

02:23.120 --> 02:25.531
Oh, thanks for coming
down to D.C. with me.

02:25.556 --> 02:29.148
Of course. Hey, telling
that woman she needs to retire

02:29.235 --> 02:31.460
- is definitely a two-woman job.
- Yeah.

02:31.485 --> 02:33.787
She can't be on her feet all day
chasing after teenagers.

02:33.946 --> 02:36.000
She's lucky she only
bruised it this time.

02:36.539 --> 02:39.179
She keeps this up, she's gonna
break the damn hip all over again.

02:39.204 --> 02:41.219
Mm, we need to get in
there and lay down the law.

02:41.244 --> 02:42.500
♪ Amen. ♪

02:42.585 --> 02:44.851
You are gonna lay down
the law with me, right?

02:45.095 --> 02:47.129
Not just lay down?

02:47.224 --> 02:49.843
Uh... what's that supposed to mean?

02:50.039 --> 02:51.953
Beth, when it comes
to standing up to your mom,

02:51.978 --> 02:54.921
you have this... tendency to clam up.

02:54.946 --> 02:56.296
I do... What?!

02:56.393 --> 02:59.218
- I do not clam up.
- You do. You clam.

02:59.379 --> 03:02.445
I get it. She's terrifying.

03:03.112 --> 03:05.141
I bet she's driving you crazy
about losing your job, right?

03:05.165 --> 03:07.992
- Nope. Not really.
- Seriously?

03:08.370 --> 03:11.632
She's not all over you
about finding something new?

03:12.625 --> 03:14.312
(IMITATES CAROL): "Gap in your résumé

03:14.403 --> 03:17.570
is a red flag for
any future employer, Bethany."

03:17.758 --> 03:19.875
No. She's been pretty cool, actually.

03:21.379 --> 03:24.523
Oh, my God. You haven't told her
you got laid off.

03:24.548 --> 03:26.273
Fine, all right? She doesn't know.

03:26.298 --> 03:28.485
And I wasn't gonna tell you
until right before we walked in,

03:28.509 --> 03:29.844
because I didn't want you
to give me crap about it

03:29.868 --> 03:31.908
- the whole car ride.
- I'm not gonna give you crap.

03:31.995 --> 03:33.085
Thank you.

03:33.797 --> 03:35.665
- You know why you didn't tell her?
- Why?

03:35.878 --> 03:37.554
- You clammed up.
- I hate you.

03:37.654 --> 03:38.765
(LAUGHS)

03:39.265 --> 03:40.546
♪

03:43.223 --> 03:44.405
CAROL: <i>Bethany?</i>

03:46.588 --> 03:47.710
Bethany?

03:48.263 --> 03:51.765
Bethany. Is this homework time,
or is this drawing time?

03:52.703 --> 03:54.000
Homework time.

03:54.703 --> 03:57.662
"Is this homework time,
or is this drawing time?"

03:57.687 --> 03:59.859
- (GIGGLES)
- Miss Zoe, you have something to say?

03:59.945 --> 04:01.195
I know you're new here,

04:01.220 --> 04:03.281
but in this house, we show respect.

04:03.335 --> 04:05.195
Sorry, Mama C.

04:05.343 --> 04:06.644
All right.

04:09.179 --> 04:10.586
(BETH GIGGLES)

04:12.307 --> 04:13.960
- (JAMAICAN ACCENT): Guess who.
- (SIGHS)

04:14.599 --> 04:17.765
Someone who ate something
with mustard on it, that's who.

04:17.790 --> 04:19.670
- (LAUGHTER)
- ABE: You are a very cruel woman.

04:20.370 --> 04:21.476
But I love you.

04:21.500 --> 04:23.002
Oh! Come on!

04:23.027 --> 04:24.094
- Ew!
- (LIVELY CHATTER)

04:24.119 --> 04:25.264
- Okay, that's enough.
- (PHONE RINGING)

04:25.288 --> 04:26.960
That's enough. How was the day?

04:27.476 --> 04:29.039
- ABE (LAUGHING): Good.
- Yeah?

04:29.064 --> 04:30.130
- ABE: Yes.
- Good.

04:30.155 --> 04:33.273
Hello? Yes, this is she.

04:34.086 --> 04:35.187
What? I got in?

04:35.212 --> 04:36.554
Bethany, who are you speaking to?

04:36.579 --> 04:37.946
I got into the academy!

04:39.186 --> 04:40.656
Child, give me this phone.

04:40.681 --> 04:41.890
What academy?

04:42.230 --> 04:44.187
Hello? Who am I speaking to?

04:44.983 --> 04:47.164
I s... I see.

04:48.590 --> 04:51.851
Well, now, I have to talk
to my husband about it.

04:52.318 --> 04:54.320
I will return your call, yes.

04:56.250 --> 04:58.600
That was Vincent Kelley from
the Whitmore Ballet Academy.

04:58.625 --> 05:00.526
He came to my dance class at school,

05:00.551 --> 05:02.172
and Ms. Allen said
we should dance our best,

05:02.196 --> 05:04.625
'cause he was gonna pick
one of us to join his academy.

05:05.148 --> 05:07.101
- (ABE CHUCKLES)
- And you think this is funny?

05:08.756 --> 05:12.617
That our daughter auditioned
for a prestigious dance academy

05:12.642 --> 05:14.304
behind our backs and got in?

05:15.123 --> 05:16.523
A little, yes. (CHUCKLES)

05:16.706 --> 05:19.343
Baby, you've seen how good our girl is.

05:19.595 --> 05:21.765
It couldn't hurt
to just check the place out.

05:23.062 --> 05:25.773
She's our little island girl.

05:26.852 --> 05:28.750
She danced before she walked.

05:28.995 --> 05:30.218
Remember?

05:32.259 --> 05:33.453
(SIGHS)

05:34.494 --> 05:35.742
(WHISPERS): Okay.

05:36.329 --> 05:37.562
♪

05:42.992 --> 05:45.398
I hope she still keeps a spare
under one of these plants.

05:45.750 --> 05:46.851
They gave her a walker.

05:46.876 --> 05:49.172
I don't want her to have to
drag herself to the front door.

05:49.196 --> 05:51.255
- Please. She's probably already in bed.
- (DOOR OPENS)

05:51.279 --> 05:53.945
CAROL: I thought I heard
some rumbling around out here.

05:54.101 --> 05:56.398
Why are you two messing around
in my plants?

05:56.423 --> 06:00.328
- Hi, Mom.
- (LAUGHS) Hi.

06:00.353 --> 06:02.320
- Hi, Mama C.
- Oh.

06:02.381 --> 06:04.582
You two didn't have to drive
all the way down here.

06:04.607 --> 06:06.789
- It's just a bruised hip.
- No, we know we didn't.

06:06.814 --> 06:09.015
We wanted to.
And aren't you supposed to be

06:09.040 --> 06:11.007
staying off your feet?
And where's that walker?

06:11.032 --> 06:13.750
- The doctor told me you're...
- Lord, please. E.R. doctors.

06:13.775 --> 06:15.078
They are so dramatic.

06:15.103 --> 06:16.870
And that walker thing is for old ladies.

06:16.895 --> 06:18.929
- But you're supposed to be...
- Now, listen.

06:19.097 --> 06:20.679
I have already been lectured to

06:20.704 --> 06:22.515
by a doctor who doesn't
know me from Adam,

06:22.540 --> 06:26.039
so whatever this "take it easy"
nonsense business is

06:26.064 --> 06:28.399
you're about to spout,
I don't want to hear that.

06:30.105 --> 06:31.875
You must be starving. Come on in.

06:31.971 --> 06:33.234
I'll warm up dinner.

06:36.752 --> 06:38.921
- She's still scary as hell.
- Mm-hmm.

06:45.250 --> 06:47.151
(PIANO PLAYING
MID-TEMPO, MINOR-KEY MUSIC)

06:54.734 --> 06:57.000
So, these are my advanced students.

06:57.025 --> 06:58.734
One day this could be Bethany.

07:00.201 --> 07:02.068
How many classes does she have to take?

07:02.406 --> 07:04.414
Three classes every day after school

07:04.439 --> 07:06.674
and then all day on Saturdays.

07:06.930 --> 07:09.648
CAROL: And all of these classes
lead to what, exactly?

07:10.117 --> 07:11.263
VINCENT: Good question.

07:11.429 --> 07:13.125
Let's talk in my office, please.

07:18.502 --> 07:19.703
Baby girl.

07:23.343 --> 07:25.031
VINCENT: <i>Every year, we put on</i>

07:25.056 --> 07:28.078
a senior showcase
for our oldest dancers,

07:28.246 --> 07:29.953
featuring some of the classics:

07:30.309 --> 07:31.992
<i>Swan Lake, Giselle,</i>

07:32.017 --> 07:33.617
- some of the new works.
- CAROL: Mm-hmm.

07:33.760 --> 07:37.531
So all these years of training
are for one night of dancing.

07:39.186 --> 07:40.987
It's not one night of dancing.

07:41.099 --> 07:43.500
It's a chance to debut our students

07:43.525 --> 07:46.148
to some of the leading
ballet companies in the country.

07:46.335 --> 07:48.820
Our featured soloists
go on to have careers

07:48.845 --> 07:52.982
at the New York City Ballet,
The Royal Ballet, the Bolshoi.

07:53.007 --> 07:54.351
How many make it?

07:55.345 --> 07:56.671
Professionally.

07:58.076 --> 07:59.376
It varies.

07:59.446 --> 08:02.492
Some years, eight. Others, two.

08:03.988 --> 08:06.382
- CAROL: Two.
- Mr. and Mrs. Clarke,

08:06.407 --> 08:09.851
do you know American Ballet
Theatre has never had

08:09.876 --> 08:11.726
African American principal dancer

08:11.751 --> 08:13.552
in their 53-year-old history?

08:14.244 --> 08:17.882
Your daughter has
a remarkable raw talent.

08:19.476 --> 08:21.265
If Bethany works hard,

08:22.185 --> 08:24.031
I believe she could be the first.

08:25.951 --> 08:27.781
I believe she can do it, too.

08:28.687 --> 08:31.757
You know, she danced before she walked.

08:31.855 --> 08:33.222
That's a true story.

08:33.799 --> 08:36.070
- You know, I...
- Um, could we have a moment?

08:37.642 --> 08:39.140
In my, uh...?

08:42.158 --> 08:43.421
Yes, of course.

08:45.000 --> 08:51.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

08:56.226 --> 08:58.546
This is a very expensive program.

08:58.571 --> 09:00.939
If she goes, you... you're
gonna have to work overtime.

09:00.964 --> 09:03.210
It's okay. I don't mind.

09:03.607 --> 09:05.921
I'll probably have to teach
summer school.

09:09.986 --> 09:12.688
- Abe, you heard the odds.
- Baby...

09:13.376 --> 09:16.320
when have we ever listened to the odds?

09:19.294 --> 09:20.492
♪

09:23.211 --> 09:24.375
Come here.

09:30.318 --> 09:32.686
Okay. We're gonna do this.

09:32.711 --> 09:34.591
Your father and I,
we're gonna make this happen.

09:35.006 --> 09:37.707
But if you go here, you'll
have to give it everything.

09:37.732 --> 09:39.156
You'll have to be the best.

09:39.360 --> 09:40.727
Now, is this what you want,

09:40.752 --> 09:43.023
to work hard at dancing
every single day?

09:44.367 --> 09:45.546
Yes, Mama.

09:45.932 --> 09:47.187
♪

10:05.765 --> 10:07.289
BETH: That smells good.

10:07.314 --> 10:10.906
Yeah. "Did you put
extra Scotch bonnet pepper,"

10:10.931 --> 10:13.953
just like your father liked it?
Yes, I did. (CHUCKLES)

10:14.395 --> 10:17.546
Aw, it's too bad your brother
and sisters are not here.

10:17.752 --> 10:20.390
- They love my curry chicken.
- Mom.

10:20.492 --> 10:22.226
- We can serve ourselves.
- Hmm? Excuse me.

10:22.251 --> 10:25.835
I can ladle this cream,
thank you very much. Mm.

10:27.939 --> 10:29.257
(ZOE CLEARS THROAT)

10:31.120 --> 10:32.500
So, Mom... (CLEARS THROAT)

10:34.053 --> 10:36.144
...Zoe and I know you don't
want us running your life.

10:36.168 --> 10:37.851
- Mm.
- And we don't want to.

10:38.600 --> 10:39.726
Mm-mm.

10:40.142 --> 10:44.242
But, um, I feel like we need
to talk about your job.

10:44.937 --> 10:46.164
What about it?

10:46.871 --> 10:49.539
Well... it's a lot.

10:51.343 --> 10:52.484
A lot?

10:54.236 --> 10:56.445
It... it takes a toll.

11:00.897 --> 11:03.789
Are there clams in this rice, Mama C?

11:04.539 --> 11:06.110
'Cause it's feeling
pretty clammy in here.

11:06.134 --> 11:07.134
(QUIETLY): Shut up.

11:07.159 --> 11:08.375
I...

11:08.759 --> 11:11.195
We were thinking that...

11:11.764 --> 11:13.031
(EXHALES)

11:13.554 --> 11:16.062
- May...
- Look, we think it's time you...

11:16.249 --> 11:17.783
thought about retiring.

11:18.820 --> 11:20.562
Are you kidding me? Are you...

11:21.312 --> 11:23.125
You want me to walk away from my job

11:23.150 --> 11:24.406
because of a bruised hip?

11:24.431 --> 11:26.949
Well, maybe retiring's extreme,
but there must be a way

11:26.973 --> 11:28.071
- for you to cut back.
- I have told you,

11:28.095 --> 11:30.468
I do not want to hear this,
especially from you.

11:31.632 --> 11:32.968
And what's that supposed to mean?

11:33.014 --> 11:34.312
What do you know about a job?

11:34.337 --> 11:35.782
BETH: Wait, Mom,
what are you talking about?

11:35.806 --> 11:37.484
- Zoe has a job.
- I'm not talking

11:37.509 --> 11:38.876
about a passion project, dear.

11:38.901 --> 11:40.898
- I'm talking about a path.
- Mm-hmm.

11:40.923 --> 11:42.804
I'm talking about choosing a real path

11:42.829 --> 11:44.687
and sticking to it, like Bethany did.

11:44.712 --> 11:47.413
Bethany went to college.
Bethany got her master's.

11:47.679 --> 11:50.351
And, every morning, Bethany wakes
up with a sense of purpose,

11:50.376 --> 11:52.664
- because Bethany...
- Bethany got laid off months ago.

11:55.441 --> 11:56.664
(SILVERWARE CLINKS)

11:59.641 --> 12:01.937
Five, six, seven, eight.

12:04.594 --> 12:05.750
Clarke.

12:07.421 --> 12:08.851
<i>Tendu derrière.</i>

12:11.063 --> 12:12.973
You know, when I was about your age,

12:12.998 --> 12:16.125
I saw Misha perform
for the first time in <i>Giselle.</i>

12:16.476 --> 12:17.671
Shoulders.

12:18.609 --> 12:19.976
Do you know who that is?

12:20.773 --> 12:23.609
The greatest of our time,
Mikhail Baryshnikov.

12:24.672 --> 12:25.945
When he leaped,

12:25.970 --> 12:28.593
I thought to myself,
"If gravity does exist,

12:28.618 --> 12:30.398
it takes a vacation when he's onstage."

12:30.423 --> 12:32.398
He simply... soared.

12:33.273 --> 12:36.718
So, you, young lady, you've got
that flying part down.

12:36.743 --> 12:39.726
Now you need to master the technique.

12:40.338 --> 12:41.609
And you will.

12:42.840 --> 12:44.140
♪

12:44.569 --> 12:45.867
Again.

12:48.572 --> 12:49.781
♪

13:18.683 --> 13:20.517
Mind the tempo, Clarke.

13:20.852 --> 13:23.220
Pull up. Don't lose your center.

13:24.033 --> 13:25.304
♪

13:36.532 --> 13:38.118
Come talk to me after class.

13:42.759 --> 13:43.954
Nice work, girls.

13:43.979 --> 13:45.970
<i>Bethany, it's been four years.</i>

13:45.995 --> 13:47.402
We've talked about this before.

13:47.427 --> 13:50.009
You know other forms of dance
can be more forgiving.

13:50.798 --> 13:55.137
Vincent, I know I'm not built
like the perfect ballerina,

13:55.572 --> 13:57.423
but neither was Lauren Anderson.

13:57.448 --> 14:00.343
And now she's principal dancer
for the Houston Ballet.

14:00.368 --> 14:01.774
The exception, not the rule.

14:01.799 --> 14:03.700
I can be the exception, too.

14:05.740 --> 14:08.478
I've wanted this
since I was a little girl.

14:11.376 --> 14:14.937
I'm going to get the solo.
I'm going to get scouted.

14:14.962 --> 14:18.056
And, in a few years,
I'm gonna be living in London,

14:18.110 --> 14:21.946
working as the principal
ballerina with The Royal Ballet.

14:24.619 --> 14:26.454
If you really want this,
I'm still with you.

14:26.479 --> 14:28.513
But you're gonna have to work
ten times harder.

14:28.883 --> 14:30.157
You up for it?

14:38.612 --> 14:39.767
(WHISPERS): Yeah.

14:42.327 --> 14:45.110
Hi. Sorry I missed dinner.

14:45.384 --> 14:46.626
Stayed late to practice.

14:46.651 --> 14:48.532
I'm gonna have to do that
from now on. (SIGHS)

14:48.962 --> 14:50.251
You're home early.

14:50.625 --> 14:51.821
CAROL: Okay.

14:53.014 --> 14:54.251
She's home.

14:56.304 --> 14:57.509
Let's tell them.

14:59.267 --> 15:01.220
Uh, tell us what? What's up?

15:07.128 --> 15:09.853
You both know I've been, uh...

15:10.603 --> 15:12.345
coughing a lot lately.

15:13.127 --> 15:15.563
Your mama convinced me to see a doctor.

15:17.093 --> 15:19.071
And it turns out...

15:19.680 --> 15:20.821
(SIGHS)

15:21.406 --> 15:25.376
...I might be a little bit
sicker than I thought.

15:28.446 --> 15:30.165
He has lung cancer.

15:36.412 --> 15:37.977
But you don't smoke.

15:38.955 --> 15:40.204
I know.

15:40.843 --> 15:42.454
So unfair, right?

15:43.942 --> 15:44.978
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

15:45.003 --> 15:46.937
I might as well start.

15:47.167 --> 15:50.002
CAROL: We told your brother
and your sisters this afternoon.

15:50.347 --> 15:52.899
The doctor wants your father
to start chemotherapy,

15:52.924 --> 15:54.696
so that's what we're going to do.

15:57.111 --> 15:58.751
Wipe those tears.

15:59.433 --> 16:00.954
We have to be strong.

16:03.397 --> 16:04.602
Come on.

16:04.990 --> 16:07.016
This table isn't gonna clear itself.

16:07.041 --> 16:08.509
Can you give us a minute?

16:09.532 --> 16:11.433
We just found out the man has cancer.

16:11.542 --> 16:14.899
And your auntie told you
what we're going to do about it.

16:14.924 --> 16:17.103
Go now. Help her clean up.

16:20.890 --> 16:22.102
♪

16:22.220 --> 16:23.329
(SNIFFLES)

16:28.037 --> 16:29.337
BETH: <i>Mom,</i>

16:29.362 --> 16:32.329
can you please talk to me?

16:33.073 --> 16:35.208
You've barely said a word in 20 minutes.

16:35.233 --> 16:36.423
Okay.

16:37.171 --> 16:39.973
Let's start with how you've been
lying to me for months.

16:41.048 --> 16:42.923
I was always planning on telling you.

16:42.948 --> 16:44.853
I just needed
to figure things out first.

16:44.878 --> 16:47.884
- Have you?
- No, not yet.

16:48.095 --> 16:50.630
I've been interviewing,
figuring out my options.

16:50.655 --> 16:51.876
Okay.

16:52.507 --> 16:54.806
Okay, we will sort all this out.

16:54.831 --> 16:57.001
Tomorrow morning,
I will brew a pot of coffee,

16:57.026 --> 16:59.595
and we will make a list of all
the great firms in your city.

16:59.620 --> 17:01.478
Then, together,
we will proof your résumé,

17:01.503 --> 17:03.501
go to Staples, get some fancy paper,

17:03.526 --> 17:05.127
and begin mailing them out.

17:05.884 --> 17:07.247
Mailing it out?

17:07.348 --> 17:09.298
I'm sorry, did we step
through a portal to 1998?

17:09.323 --> 17:10.712
Don't be smart.

17:15.640 --> 17:16.876
♪

17:23.330 --> 17:24.884
(DISHES CLINKING QUIETLY)

17:29.293 --> 17:30.860
I'm going to quit dance.

17:32.216 --> 17:33.923
What are you talking about?

17:38.199 --> 17:39.501
It's my fault.

17:42.423 --> 17:43.470
He's...

17:44.144 --> 17:45.431
He worked too hard.

17:45.615 --> 17:47.728
- And now it might...
- Bethany, stop.

17:48.501 --> 17:50.743
It is not your fault
that your father is sick.

17:50.768 --> 17:52.970
And you are not gonna give up
years of training.

17:52.995 --> 17:54.899
You're gonna stick
to the path you chose,

17:54.924 --> 17:56.462
and you will be the best.

17:57.483 --> 17:58.634
♪

18:10.187 --> 18:11.532
VINCENT: I trust you're warm?

18:11.932 --> 18:13.766
We're gonna learn a new combination.

18:13.791 --> 18:15.454
Sonya here will demonstrate.

18:17.151 --> 18:18.438
♪

18:35.809 --> 18:37.710
(SPORTSCAST PLAYING OVER TV, DOOR OPENS)

18:38.131 --> 18:39.965
ANNOUNCER:
There was an appeal, but that...

18:40.489 --> 18:43.161
Hi, Mom. Dad. Zo.

18:44.840 --> 18:46.996
Mm, this is late, even for you.

18:47.195 --> 18:49.096
CAROL: When will you hear
about the solo?

18:49.246 --> 18:50.931
I need time to make your costume.

18:51.262 --> 18:52.333
Eight weeks.

18:52.746 --> 18:53.942
Okay.

18:55.567 --> 18:57.105
(CLICKS TONGUE)
Time for bed, young lady.

18:57.129 --> 18:58.981
You've been watching TV for hours now.

18:59.074 --> 19:01.192
(SIGHS) It's not even that late. Chill.

19:02.091 --> 19:06.676
I know you did not
just tell <i>me</i> to chill, <i>child.</i>

19:07.349 --> 19:08.543
(LAUGHING)

19:10.305 --> 19:13.374
That girl is giving your mother
a run for her money.

19:18.552 --> 19:22.082
So, tell me, what is it
you all are working on?

19:22.107 --> 19:23.197
<i>Pigeon Lake?</i>

19:23.402 --> 19:24.597
(CHUCKLES)

19:25.770 --> 19:27.520
It's <i>Swan Lake,</i> Dad.

19:28.146 --> 19:31.098
(CHUCKLES) There it is,
that smile I missed.

19:34.643 --> 19:36.739
We got a new girl in class today.

19:37.079 --> 19:39.582
Oh? She any good?

19:41.251 --> 19:42.692
Better than good.

19:43.491 --> 19:45.067
I work hard, but...

19:45.874 --> 19:48.020
it just comes easier to her.

19:48.231 --> 19:49.278
I can tell.

19:49.418 --> 19:50.434
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

19:51.743 --> 19:53.778
My baby girl.

19:54.223 --> 19:56.997
18 months old
before you started walking.

19:57.022 --> 19:58.200
Yeah, I know, Dad.

19:58.230 --> 20:00.590
And your mother was scared to death.

20:01.457 --> 20:03.571
She took you to all kind of doctors.

20:03.596 --> 20:05.965
Wanted to find out
what was wrong with you.

20:06.897 --> 20:09.129
But nobody could tell her anything.

20:10.362 --> 20:14.165
And then, one day,
we were all in Kingston.

20:14.516 --> 20:17.127
Uncle Clem put on some Burning Spear.

20:17.152 --> 20:19.219
- You know the song?
- "Dread River."

20:19.282 --> 20:20.465
(CHUCKLES)

20:20.923 --> 20:24.840
That song started playing,
and it seem like

20:24.865 --> 20:27.967
it just pick you
right up off the ground,

20:28.254 --> 20:32.504
because you stood and
you danced straight over to me.

20:33.825 --> 20:37.262
Your mama would never
admit it now, but she sobbed.

20:37.572 --> 20:39.192
We were so happy.

20:40.501 --> 20:42.809
Our little island girl,

20:43.860 --> 20:46.629
who dance before she walked.

20:48.496 --> 20:49.786
That's who you are.

20:50.231 --> 20:51.387
♪

20:51.523 --> 20:53.254
Never forget, baby girl.

20:55.261 --> 20:56.457
I won't.

21:01.407 --> 21:02.692
(BOTH CHUCKLE)

21:04.641 --> 21:05.840
(SIGHS)

21:07.569 --> 21:08.731
Okay.

21:16.165 --> 21:17.598
(ABE COUGHS)

21:19.848 --> 21:22.496
- Dad?
- Yes, my love?

21:25.231 --> 21:26.403
Nothing.

21:26.988 --> 21:28.942
- Good night.
- Good night.

21:30.217 --> 21:31.340
♪

21:37.629 --> 21:38.755
(QUIET KNOCK ON DOOR)

21:39.309 --> 21:40.457
Come in.

21:44.114 --> 21:46.137
- You up?
- Hell yeah.

21:46.442 --> 21:49.207
Past 20 years have not been kind
to this mattress.

21:49.244 --> 21:51.543
Come with me.
I got something to show you.

22:01.681 --> 22:02.981
(BETH CHUCKLES)

22:03.074 --> 22:04.426
(QUIETLY): What are you doing?

22:06.893 --> 22:08.231
(GASPS, MOUTHS)

22:09.668 --> 22:11.059
Zoe Marie Baker,

22:11.084 --> 22:12.918
did you hide drugs behind Big Mama?

22:12.943 --> 22:14.521
It's the only sacred place in the house.

22:14.545 --> 22:16.969
(WHISPERING): Lower your voice.
She might hear us.

22:16.994 --> 22:18.305
Is it still good? (SNIFFS)

22:18.854 --> 22:20.461
- Yeah, she's still good.
- (GIGGLES)

22:22.248 --> 22:24.547
I will never let you
tweeze my eyebrows again.

22:25.133 --> 22:26.586
(LAUGHS): I was a kid.

22:27.430 --> 22:28.964
So was I.

22:28.989 --> 22:30.797
- With no eyebrows.
- (BOTH LAUGH)

22:32.961 --> 22:36.864
I am sorry that my mom
laid into you like that.

22:37.061 --> 22:40.397
- About your documentaries.
- Mm. It's fine.

22:41.641 --> 22:43.985
It really is fine with you, isn't it?

22:44.907 --> 22:47.634
Man, I would carry
that crap around inside of me

22:47.659 --> 22:49.258
- for, like, a year.
- Mm.

22:49.283 --> 22:53.266
But you, you just explode,
and it's all over for you.

22:53.782 --> 22:54.883
Mm.

22:55.485 --> 22:57.961
Well, I think it's always been
different for me.

22:58.947 --> 23:02.016
I mean, by the time
I came to live in this house...

23:02.251 --> 23:03.383
(EXHALES)

23:04.986 --> 23:07.047
Well, it was safe here.

23:08.204 --> 23:10.766
And, uh, well, the rest of you,
you looked at your mom

23:10.791 --> 23:13.516
like she was this strict,
domineering woman, and...

23:14.870 --> 23:16.289
I just saw this...

23:17.212 --> 23:20.149
this person that couldn't hurt
me like I'd been hurt before.

23:23.047 --> 23:24.289
You know what?

23:25.205 --> 23:28.907
We don't talk enough about
how incredible you turned out

23:28.932 --> 23:31.711
despite all the crap
you were put through.

23:36.392 --> 23:37.492
No. (CHUCKLES)

23:37.692 --> 23:39.071
We really don't.

23:42.071 --> 23:44.266
But, uh, but your mom, she...

23:45.234 --> 23:47.164
she went easier on me, too.

23:47.603 --> 23:51.139
But the rest of you?
She... she was tough.

23:53.143 --> 23:57.071
Sister-cousin,
I know you inside and out,

23:57.096 --> 24:00.565
and something bigger
is going on with you.

24:01.461 --> 24:03.891
And you need to find a way
to talk about it

24:05.151 --> 24:07.024
before all that pressure...

24:07.840 --> 24:09.094
(IMITATES EXPLOSION)

24:11.400 --> 24:12.602
What was that?

24:13.931 --> 24:15.961
Uh, was supposed to be an explosion.

24:17.461 --> 24:18.774
I'm pretty high.

24:19.675 --> 24:20.883
(BOTH LAUGHING)

24:23.310 --> 24:24.617
♪

24:30.938 --> 24:32.274
(BOTH CHUCKLE)

24:35.321 --> 24:36.703
(WHISPERING): I'll be up in a minute.

24:36.727 --> 24:39.167
- (WHISPERING): Okay. Good night, cuz.
- All right. Night cuz.

24:40.717 --> 24:42.383
ABE: <i>Never forget, baby girl.</i>

24:43.826 --> 24:45.071
♪

24:53.316 --> 24:54.438
(ABE COUGHS)

24:56.955 --> 24:59.539
- Dad?
- Yes, my love?

25:00.767 --> 25:02.274
BETH: <i>I'm gonna forget.</i>

25:05.366 --> 25:07.391
I'm gonna forget that part of me.

25:12.759 --> 25:14.774
Dad, I want you to know that I'll...

25:16.063 --> 25:17.352
be happy.

25:19.564 --> 25:22.433
I'll find love. Great love, oh.

25:24.199 --> 25:26.934
With a man who reminds me
so much of you it's scary.

25:27.565 --> 25:28.836
(CRYING SOFTLY)

25:32.310 --> 25:34.469
But I can't be me without you.

25:38.996 --> 25:40.211
How could I be?

25:45.631 --> 25:47.992
Nothing. Good night.

25:58.930 --> 26:01.157
- (QUIET CHATTER)
- I know. I'm really excited, though.

26:02.244 --> 26:04.746
- Yeah, I know.
- Oh, hey, Bethany.

26:04.771 --> 26:06.133
Hey.

26:06.682 --> 26:07.969
(CHATTER CONTINUES)

26:13.727 --> 26:16.539
We were all real sorry
to hear about your dad passing.

26:16.860 --> 26:19.438
Mr. Kelley said you were gonna
at least take a couple days off.

26:19.463 --> 26:21.758
- Did you...
- I'd rather be here with you guys.

26:22.859 --> 26:24.760
Plus, I already broke two lamps

26:24.785 --> 26:26.426
- trying to rehearse at home.
- (CHUCKLES)

26:28.655 --> 26:29.837
The list is up. (CHUCKLES)

26:32.338 --> 26:33.415
♪

26:37.168 --> 26:38.353
(EXCITED CHATTER)

26:56.437 --> 26:58.509
I didn't expect to see you back so soon.

27:00.095 --> 27:02.157
Yeah, but my dad
would have wanted me to be here.

27:02.750 --> 27:05.040
Believe me, Bethany,
I wish it could've been you.

27:10.021 --> 27:11.681
I want you ready in five minutes.

27:12.819 --> 27:13.915
♪

27:23.554 --> 27:24.681
Hi.

27:27.425 --> 27:28.610
Mom?

27:30.790 --> 27:32.079
Mom, are you okay?

27:33.806 --> 27:35.485
I picked up some Chinese food

27:35.510 --> 27:38.002
after dropping your brother and
sisters off at the train station.

27:38.026 --> 27:39.173
Are you hungry?

27:41.189 --> 27:42.868
Mom, if you're sad, we can talk.

27:42.893 --> 27:45.195
- We can...
- Of course I'm sad, Bethany.

27:45.708 --> 27:47.306
What else could I be?

27:48.783 --> 27:50.250
How was dance today?

27:52.360 --> 27:55.431
Uh, they announced the cast
for the senior showcase.

27:59.628 --> 28:01.485
I didn't get the solo.

28:07.999 --> 28:10.095
(VOICE BREAKING): I worked really hard.

28:12.483 --> 28:14.329
I'm sorry if I disappointed you.

28:16.328 --> 28:17.853
You did your best.

28:18.408 --> 28:20.157
That's all I ever asked.

28:20.769 --> 28:23.110
Don't worry, Mom. I'm not gonna give up.

28:23.435 --> 28:24.668
(SNIFFLES)

28:35.579 --> 28:37.039
(CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING)

28:46.113 --> 28:47.368
Oh.

28:47.771 --> 28:49.905
- (MUSIC STOPS)
- Sorry. Is the music bothering you?

28:49.930 --> 28:52.345
I just wanted to practice
a little bit before bed.

28:52.386 --> 28:55.610
Bethany, come sit here.
I have something for you.

28:56.290 --> 28:59.149
I gave this to your sisters
and your brother.

28:59.174 --> 29:00.868
It helped them choose their colleges.

29:03.656 --> 29:05.142
But you know I'm not...

29:05.875 --> 29:08.812
I mean, the plan is
for me to get into a company.

29:08.837 --> 29:10.189
That <i>was</i> the plan.

29:10.714 --> 29:13.182
But now we have to choose
a different path for you.

29:15.387 --> 29:16.626
A different path?

29:18.235 --> 29:20.485
I'm sorry. I-I really am.

29:23.032 --> 29:25.220
But I just don't see dance
as a path for you.

29:26.353 --> 29:29.618
And I cannot watch you move to New York

29:29.643 --> 29:32.970
and struggle to make ends meet
while you audition for companies

29:32.995 --> 29:34.845
that you're never going to get into.

29:35.002 --> 29:36.946
I won't continue to pay for this school.

29:38.233 --> 29:39.946
It's setting you up to fail.

29:40.755 --> 29:41.985
♪

30:10.345 --> 30:12.246
Mom? What are you doing?

30:13.063 --> 30:14.329
- (EXHALES)
- It's 3:00 a.m.

30:14.649 --> 30:15.853
Oh, I couldn't sleep,

30:15.878 --> 30:18.696
so I thought I'd get
a head start on listing firms.

30:19.549 --> 30:21.720
I really don't need you
to help me find me a job, Mom.

30:21.914 --> 30:24.454
It's okay. I'm happy to help.

30:25.307 --> 30:26.978
Well, I'm not happy to have your help.

30:31.137 --> 30:32.782
I know you're embarrassed.

30:34.060 --> 30:35.805
But you don't have to be
rude to... (GROANS)

30:36.365 --> 30:37.571
to me.

30:39.977 --> 30:43.735
Yeah. Just keep on going
like you always do, right, Mom?

30:45.405 --> 30:46.696
Even in pain.

30:48.235 --> 30:49.923
That's what Clarke women do, right?

30:50.245 --> 30:51.782
No room for weakness.

30:52.845 --> 30:55.884
Dad dies, we just wipe our tears
and keep on marching, right?

30:56.222 --> 30:57.915
And what would you have had us do?

30:58.008 --> 30:59.509
Wallow in our grief?

31:00.782 --> 31:01.993
No.

31:02.427 --> 31:04.485
But we could've taken some time.

31:13.983 --> 31:16.329
Mom, I remember feeling so free...

31:17.259 --> 31:18.860
when I was a little girl.

31:20.763 --> 31:22.110
Do you remember that?

31:24.630 --> 31:26.282
I always had my head in the clouds,

31:26.307 --> 31:29.103
and I was always... doodling and...

31:31.886 --> 31:33.220
...always dancing.

31:34.357 --> 31:36.618
- Bethany.
- You didn't have to take it from me.

31:39.520 --> 31:41.751
You had gone as far
as you could go, Bethany.

31:41.776 --> 31:43.189
It wasn't working out for you.

31:43.258 --> 31:46.027
You had gone as far as you could go.

31:49.635 --> 31:53.884
You ever wonder why Lisa, Isaiah
and Renee don't come around?

31:57.268 --> 31:58.923
It's because of how you are.

32:00.779 --> 32:03.047
There's no air around you.

32:04.522 --> 32:06.743
There's no air to breathe.

32:07.969 --> 32:10.360
No air to be sad. No air to fail.

32:13.708 --> 32:15.407
That's your big complaint?

32:15.782 --> 32:17.118
No air?

32:18.890 --> 32:20.431
Well, I can live with that.

32:21.735 --> 32:25.157
I promised my mother I'd push my
kids as hard as she pushed me.

32:25.717 --> 32:27.681
My kids may not come around,

32:27.793 --> 32:30.361
but that's okay with me
because I know you're all good.

32:30.386 --> 32:32.048
But I'm not good, Mom.

32:33.394 --> 32:34.814
I am not good.

32:35.922 --> 32:38.517
I haven't had my head
in the clouds for years.

32:39.235 --> 32:41.514
My husband, he dreams, oh.

32:41.946 --> 32:44.087
He dreams these big ideas,

32:44.112 --> 32:46.134
and he is never ashamed to do it,

32:46.159 --> 32:48.681
because nobody ever made him
feel like he should be.

32:49.565 --> 32:50.728
But me?

32:52.681 --> 32:53.814
I can't even look at him.

32:53.839 --> 32:55.962
I can't even look at the person

32:55.987 --> 32:57.462
closest to me in the whole world.

32:57.487 --> 32:59.814
I cannot look him in the eye...

33:00.411 --> 33:01.673
♪

33:02.906 --> 33:05.595
...tell him I want to be that
little girl who dances again.

33:14.214 --> 33:15.376
(GRUNTS)

33:17.851 --> 33:19.149
♪

33:33.361 --> 33:35.142
This sweater looks good on you, Bethany.

33:35.167 --> 33:36.853
And I like the braids.

33:37.143 --> 33:39.306
A freshman college mixer.

33:39.902 --> 33:44.728
This is a fresh start
filled with great opportunities.

33:46.712 --> 33:47.993
♪

34:53.195 --> 34:54.757
- Oh. I-I'm sorry.
- Oh.

34:55.163 --> 34:56.467
No problem.

35:15.391 --> 35:18.593
- Mom.
- No. Let me speak.

35:24.394 --> 35:28.064
My mother was
the smartest person I ever knew.

35:29.970 --> 35:33.155
Her little restaurant
on 129th Street in Harlem

35:33.398 --> 35:36.038
helped put me and my brothers
through school.

35:36.063 --> 35:39.358
My father thought education
was worthless for a girl,

35:39.893 --> 35:41.663
but she stood up to him.

35:42.067 --> 35:45.202
Told him I would have every
opportunity my brothers had.

35:46.427 --> 35:48.397
She worked hard for me.

35:49.689 --> 35:51.866
And I worked hard to make her proud.

35:53.937 --> 35:55.655
We hardly ever fought.

35:57.137 --> 35:59.311
Except, of course,
when I met your father.

36:00.483 --> 36:02.229
Oh, sh-she warned me,

36:02.254 --> 36:05.725
"Girl, bad company
will lead you astray."

36:07.771 --> 36:09.718
But Abe wasn't bad company.

36:09.837 --> 36:12.257
He just didn't take life so seriously.

36:15.009 --> 36:17.163
I had so many worries.

36:18.319 --> 36:20.335
Sometimes those worries suffocated me.

36:20.360 --> 36:23.741
But when I was with him,

36:24.631 --> 36:27.038
I felt like I could finally breathe.

36:28.858 --> 36:30.054
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

36:30.621 --> 36:34.741
I guess he gave me that air that
you said I don't have on my own.

36:37.296 --> 36:39.546
Which is why I fell in love with him.

36:41.078 --> 36:42.936
And your grandmother came around.

36:43.598 --> 36:47.546
She came home one night;
Abe was over visiting me.

36:49.913 --> 36:53.248
He had brought me dinner
while I was cramming for exams.

36:55.240 --> 36:57.007
And he was feeding me.

36:58.272 --> 37:01.444
Literally, feeding me
one forkful at a time,

37:02.294 --> 37:05.116
because I wouldn't stop studying
to pick up a fork.

37:07.311 --> 37:10.446
And she saw that he was
exactly what I needed.

37:12.646 --> 37:15.983
I was too serious;
he wasn't serious enough.

37:18.009 --> 37:20.491
But together we made
the perfect balance.

37:26.877 --> 37:30.241
Bethany, I don't know if I made
the right decision for you.

37:32.545 --> 37:35.380
But I didn't have time
to question myself.

37:36.897 --> 37:38.514
Your father was gone.

37:38.988 --> 37:41.819
My air was gone.

37:42.034 --> 37:43.257
And...

37:43.887 --> 37:46.702
I just had me and my worries,

37:48.198 --> 37:51.007
wanting my last child to be okay.

37:52.723 --> 37:54.655
Our little island girl,

37:55.534 --> 37:58.241
who danced before she could walk.

37:58.587 --> 37:59.843
(CHUCKLES)

38:00.517 --> 38:01.655
(WHISPERS): Mom.

38:08.582 --> 38:10.389
